<!-- Author - Chrissy Safranski -->
<!-- Limit Definition of the Derivative at a point, progressively less info given -->

<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="a" from="-4" to="4" exclude="0"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="b" from="-5" to="5" exclude="0 $a"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="c" from="-6" to="6" exclude="0 $a $b"/>
  <function name="quad1">$a x^2+ $b x +$c </function>
  <derivative name="quad1prime"> $quad1 </derivative>
  <function name="quad2">$b x^2+ $c x +$a </function>
  <derivative name="quad2prime"> $quad2 </derivative>  
  <function name="quad3">$c x^2+ $a x +$b </function>
  <derivative name="quad3prime"> $quad3 </derivative>    
</setup>

<p>
  Recall that the limit definition of the derivative tells us that 
  <me>
    f'(x) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}.
  </me>
  In the sequence of questions that follow, you'll be given enough information about a function <m>f</m> whose formula you don't know so that you can use the limit definition to find the corresponding formula for <m>f'(x)</m>.  Note that from question to question, <m>f</m> will usually be a different function. 
</p>

<p>
  <ol marker="a.">
    <li>
      <setup>
        <math name="num1" simplify expand>$$quad1(x+h)-$$quad1(x)</math>
      </setup>
      <p>Suppose that <m>f(x)</m> is a function for which
      <me> f'(x)=\lim_{h\to 0} \frac{$num1}{h}.</me>
      Determine <m>f'(x).</m></p>
      <p><m>f'(x)=</m><answer name="calclimit">$$quad1prime(x)</answer></p>
    <!--   add feedback hint after 2 wrong attempts to factor the numerator and then divide the h's. Also add randomization -->
    </li>
    <li>
      <setup>
        <math name="num2" simplify expand>$$quad2(x+h)-$$quad2(x)</math>
      </setup>
      <p>Next, assume that <m>f(x)</m> is a function for which
      <me> \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}= \frac{$num2}{h}.</me>
      Determine <m>f'(x).</m></p>

      <p><m>f'(x)=</m><answer name="givendiffquot">$$quad2prime(x)</answer></p>
    <!--   add feedback hint after 2 wrong attempts to use the limit def of the deriv, f'(1)=lim_{h\to 0} \frac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}, so we're looking for the limit of this as h goes to 0. -->
    </li>
    <li>
      <setup>
        <math name="num3" simplify expand>$$quad3(x+h)-$$quad3(x)</math>
      </setup>
      <p>Now, say that <m>f(x)</m> is a function for which
      <me> f(x+h)-f(x)= $num3.</me>
      Determine <m>f'(x).</m></p>

      <p><m>f'(x)=</m><answer name="givennumerator">$$quad3prime(x)</answer></p>
      <!--   add feedback hint after 2 wrong attempts to use the limit def of the deriv, f'(1)=lim_{h\to 0} \frac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}, so we put this in the numerator, divide by h, and take the limit of this as h goes to 0. -->
    </li>
    <li>

      <p>Say that <m>f(x)=<math>$quad1</math></m>.
      Use the limit definition of the derivative to determine the exact value of <m>f'(x).</m></p>

      <p><m>f'(x)=</m><answer name="givenfunction">$$quad1prime(x)</answer></p>
    <!--   add feedback hint after 2 wrong attempts to use the limit def of the deriv, f'(1)=lim_{h\to 0} \frac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}, so we put this in the numerator, divide by h, and take the limit of this as h goes to 0. -->
    </li>
  </ol>
</p>